metadata.name: Entropes #4
metadata.description:
Entropes is an abstract generative art project consisting of patterns and textures made with a heuristic rectangle packing algorithm. It‚Äôs a blend of shapes, geometry and colour. It draws notable inspiration from the Bauhaus art style. All these attributes are fused to form aesthetics that create diversity while maintaining cohesiveness across this body of work.

_____________________________________________________________________________________

The details go down to the very last pixel and outputs can be saved right from the browser at a full resolution of 6400 x 9600 pixels which ensures the quality holds up across majority of displays and different print sizes.

_____________________________________________________________________________________

Programmed entirely using p5js.

_____________________________________________________________________________________

A project by Kamau Kamau and Ian Wright

metadata.name: Absorbed #300
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF‚Äôs Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT‚Ñ¢). 

MAT‚Ñ¢ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT‚Ñ¢. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed ‚Äì high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and ‚Äúsinusoidal‚Äù noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists‚Äô belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica‚Äôs companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: Miniscapes #353
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: singularity #2
metadata.description:
Within the vast expanse of the digital universe, a peculiar abnormality calls out to us‚Äîa gaze, not formed by organic matter but existing in a realm of pixels, delves into the recesses of our creative thoughts. This unique artwork is not sculpted or painted, but emerges from the intricate interplay between code and probability, like a mesmerizing choreography of algorithms.

At the core of this piece, there lies a vast emptiness, a gaping void that resembles a black gemstone, capable of devouring every stray dot on the screen. This is the essence of it all, a virtual singularity where the familiar merges with the limitless possibilities of imagination.

In the realm of artistry, there exists a profound interplay between order and chaos. Every single strand of color is methodically planned, yet somehow emanates an organic sense of unpredictability. This delicate duality resonates with the very essence of the universe, where the seemingly chaotic multitude of stars discovers its place within the majestic framework of galaxies.

It is an experience, crafted by the meticulous madness of algorithms, that this piece does not stand as a mere image but rather a portal to dimensions to be viewed.
